WEBVTT

00:00.320 --> 00:02.960
So this is just kind of a brief overview

00:02.960 --> 00:04.800
on some helper things that you can do with React

00:04.800 --> 00:07.960
just to kind of like make it easier to work with.

00:07.960 --> 00:10.640
So one of them is, we're using Vite,

00:10.640 --> 00:13.440
so Vite will take care of NodeM for you automatically,

00:13.440 --> 00:14.760
but NodeM, if you're not familiar with it,

00:14.760 --> 00:16.740
is just basically telling the tools

00:16.740 --> 00:17.580
that you're working with,

00:17.580 --> 00:18.840
is like, am I in development mode

00:18.840 --> 00:20.200
or am I in production mode?

00:20.200 --> 00:22.800
And usually it's assumed that you're in production mode

00:22.800 --> 00:24.560
and then you only set it to development mode

00:24.560 --> 00:27.160
when you're actually doing dev work.

00:27.160 --> 00:29.280
This used to be a thing that you had to set it explicitly,

00:29.320 --> 00:30.400
and that's why I still mention it here.

00:30.400 --> 00:31.580
So if you're doing like webpack,

00:31.580 --> 00:33.300
you might still have to set it explicitly

00:33.300 --> 00:36.660
of like, I'm in dev mode right now.

00:36.660 --> 00:39.880
This is important to React because React has a lot

00:39.880 --> 00:42.800
of like helpers and better error messages

00:42.800 --> 00:45.040
and all that kind of stuff when you're in dev mode,

00:45.040 --> 00:48.920
but the actual executable of React is a lot slower

00:48.920 --> 00:51.200
and it's four times bigger.

00:51.200 --> 00:52.320
So, or at least that's what it was,

00:52.320 --> 00:53.680
I haven't checked recently how big it is,

00:53.680 --> 00:55.260
but it was quite big.

00:56.900 --> 00:58.120
So if you're using Vite,

00:58.120 --> 00:59.840
if you're following along with me,

00:59.840 --> 01:01.680
if you're using Next, if you're using Remix,

01:01.680 --> 01:04.280
they all set NodeM for you automatically.

01:04.280 --> 01:06.400
If you're using something like webpack directly,

01:06.400 --> 01:08.040
you might have to set it yourself.

01:09.400 --> 01:10.720
One of the reasons I also bring this up

01:10.720 --> 01:14.480
is that make sure this gets set to production

01:14.480 --> 01:17.080
when you actually do go out to production.

01:17.080 --> 01:18.000
That becomes important.

01:18.000 --> 01:20.780
Famously Slack shipped React in dev mode

01:20.780 --> 01:22.600
for a very, very long time,

01:22.600 --> 01:24.320
and they actually saw a massive increase

01:24.320 --> 01:26.520
in like performance at Slack

01:26.520 --> 01:27.840
because all they had to do was

01:27.840 --> 01:30.000
switch NodeM to production, right?

01:30.000 --> 01:31.900
Which is a very dumb reason

01:31.900 --> 01:35.040
to waste a lot of people's time and resources, right?

01:35.040 --> 01:36.900
So, that's one.

01:38.680 --> 01:41.320
Strict mode, let's go do that right now.

01:43.560 --> 01:48.560
So, strict mode is a kind of React mode

01:49.680 --> 01:50.680
you can set things in.

01:50.680 --> 01:52.720
So we're just gonna go to app.jsx

01:53.720 --> 01:56.880
and we're gonna say at the top,

01:57.760 --> 02:02.760
import strict mode from React,

02:04.560 --> 02:07.720
and we're just gonna wrap our entire app in it.

02:07.720 --> 02:09.160
Strict mode.

02:14.220 --> 02:15.440
So, what is strict mode?

02:15.440 --> 02:17.440
It's just like an extra set of checks

02:17.440 --> 02:21.120
that React will do things for you normally,

02:21.120 --> 02:22.600
but in strict mode it'll say like,

02:22.600 --> 02:25.480
hey, you're executing in strict mode,

02:25.480 --> 02:27.000
I'm not gonna let you do this.

02:28.120 --> 02:31.140
Usually what it is, is like,

02:31.140 --> 02:32.680
if you're using things that are about

02:32.680 --> 02:34.120
to be removed from React,

02:34.120 --> 02:34.960
it'll give you a big warning.

02:34.960 --> 02:37.800
It's like, hey, this has been warned

02:37.800 --> 02:38.720
that this is gonna be removed

02:38.720 --> 02:40.000
from a future version of React.

02:40.000 --> 02:41.120
I'm not going to let you use this

02:41.120 --> 02:42.840
because you're in strict mode.

02:42.840 --> 02:45.360
So they do that so that people know in advance

02:45.360 --> 02:47.280
that stuff's gonna be removed from React.

02:47.280 --> 02:49.360
So, that's what strict mode is.

02:50.220 --> 02:51.880
Yeah, continue to double render your components

02:51.880 --> 02:54.880
just to make sure that all the effects are run twice, right?

02:56.120 --> 02:57.860
It can catch subtle bugs of like,

02:57.860 --> 02:59.960
sometimes you have effects that are doing something one time

02:59.960 --> 03:01.440
and working differently another time.

03:01.440 --> 03:03.640
That's kind of what they're supposed to catch.

03:05.040 --> 03:06.320
If you're asking me how many times

03:06.320 --> 03:07.360
has that caught something for me,

03:07.360 --> 03:08.480
the answer is not really,

03:08.480 --> 03:10.240
because like once you're in the mindset

03:10.240 --> 03:13.040
of like how effects and state is supposed to work,

03:13.040 --> 03:15.980
it's pretty rare that you would get outside of that.

