08:51.140 --> 08:53.980
or maybe in a different React performance course.

08:56.140 --> 08:59.380
One thing, just kind of as a general note with React,

08:59.380 --> 09:01.820
it's generally fast enough.

09:02.700 --> 09:04.340
And when I say that, you kind of get to write,

09:04.340 --> 09:07.180
React can be fairly naive in terms of like

09:07.180 --> 09:08.540
not worrying about performance,

09:08.540 --> 09:10.160
not worrying about commits or updates

09:10.160 --> 09:11.780
or anything like that.

09:11.780 --> 09:14.700
My advice to you is just continue writing React that way

09:14.700 --> 09:15.900
for the most part.

09:15.900 --> 09:18.180
Only introduce the performance enhancements

09:18.180 --> 09:19.380
when you have a problem.

09:19.380 --> 09:22.120
So state it differently, solve problems you have.

09:22.120 --> 09:24.060
Don't try to anticipate problems that you might have

09:24.060 --> 09:25.220
because you usually are wrong

09:25.220 --> 09:27.260
about the problems you're about to have.

09:30.580 --> 09:34.020
And while the performance enhancements for React work,

09:34.020 --> 09:34.860
they work great,

09:37.700 --> 09:40.420
they make the code harder to read and harder to debug.

09:41.660 --> 09:45.660
And that's why I say don't do the performance enhancements

09:45.660 --> 09:46.540
until you need them

09:46.540 --> 09:48.940
because it becomes harder to work with your code.

